but the tail goes up.

00:28:56.380 --> 00:28:57.970
And it's very nice.

00:28:57.970 --> 00:29:01.080
They're very beautiful, very
elegant, and light horses.

00:29:01.080 --> 00:29:04.310
So they can just
achieve, like, a waltz.

00:29:04.310 --> 00:29:05.540
I see it like a waltz.

00:29:05.540 --> 00:29:08.050
So that's why we have
a lot of Arabians.

00:29:08.050 --> 00:29:10.380
But that having been
said, are they easier

00:29:10.380 --> 00:29:12.450
to train than other horses?

00:29:12.450 --> 00:29:13.270
I don't think so.

00:29:13.270 --> 00:29:15.480
I think the easiest
horses to train,

00:29:15.480 --> 00:29:17.060
obviously, are the
American quarter

00:29:17.060 --> 00:29:20.780
horses, because they are cold.

00:29:20.780 --> 00:29:22.240
We call it "cold-blood."

00:29:22.240 --> 00:29:26.570
They're a little bit colder and
really nothing affects them.

00:29:26.570 --> 00:29:30.150
And you can see why
the cowboys used

00:29:30.150 --> 00:29:34.870
to shoot guns over
a quarter horse,

00:29:34.870 --> 00:29:37.940
because he's just
like, yeah, OK.

00:29:37.940 --> 00:29:39.560
Something is going on.

00:29:39.560 --> 00:29:42.090
Where, if you do that with
an Arabian, I'm telling you,

00:29:42.090 --> 00:29:45.010
he's away as far as he could.

00:29:45.010 --> 00:29:47.890
So that's why.

00:29:47.890 --> 00:29:51.890
So the Arabians like
to have movement,

00:29:51.890 --> 00:29:57.740
and that's why we have a
lot for this liberty part.

00:29:57.740 --> 00:30:00.220
AUDIENCE: What's the ideal age
that you'll introduce horses

00:30:00.220 --> 00:30:00.910
to the program?

00:30:00.910 --> 00:30:03.243
Will you take two, three
year-olds that are newly broke?

00:30:03.243 --> 00:30:04.680
Will you take a
16 year-old horse

00:30:04.680 --> 00:30:06.679
that's been doing something
else his whole life?

00:30:06.679 --> 00:30:09.335
What do you tend to aim for
with the age of your horses?

00:30:09.335 --> 00:30:11.210
NORMAND LATOURELLE:
Yeah, very good question.

00:30:11.210 --> 00:30:12.720
First, we don't breed horses.

00:30:12.720 --> 00:30:18.090
We buy horses that are
already fully-- conformated?

00:30:18.090 --> 00:30:20.770
Con-- con-- con-- what?

00:30:20.770 --> 00:30:21.810
AUDIENCE: Conformed.

00:30:21.810 --> 00:30:22.200
NORMAND LATOURELLE: Conformed.

00:30:22.200 --> 00:30:22.700
I'm sorry.

00:30:22.700 --> 00:30:23.750
Looking for the word.

00:30:23.750 --> 00:30:25.660
Fully conformed
so we know what we

00:30:25.660 --> 00:30:29.890
buy, so we know how he
looks, how he'll behave.

00:30:29.890 --> 00:30:35.380
So usually, we rarely buy
horses under three years old.

00:30:35.380 --> 00:30:37.880
Most likely, we like to
buy them at four or five,

00:30:37.880 --> 00:30:42.370
but with the minimum of being
what you call in English

00:30:42.370 --> 00:30:42.960
"broken."

00:30:42.960 --> 00:30:46.490
I don't like this word,
but that's the word we use.

00:30:46.490 --> 00:30:50.690
So minimally ridden
but not too much.

00:30:50.690 --> 00:30:53.750
Because if you take
a horse that has

00:30:53.750 --> 00:30:57.110
been trained by
somebody too difficult,

00:30:57.110 --> 00:30:59.360
then you have a difficult horse.

00:30:59.360 --> 00:31:03.660
So that's why we try to buy
them around four or five.

00:31:03.660 --> 00:31:06.410
We will sometimes
find an exception

00:31:06.410 --> 00:31:12.920
of a six, seven years old horse,
but we don't keep them on tour.

00:31:12.920 --> 00:31:14.620
There's no horses
over-- right now,

00:31:14.620 --> 00:31:18.040
I think the oldest is
16 or 17 years old.

00:31:18.040 --> 00:31:20.165
And we still have some
horses that were there

00:31:20.165 --> 00:31:23.720
in Cavalia, actually, in 2003.

00:31:23.720 --> 00:31:26.710
One of the first horses I
bought is a quarter horse.

00:31:26.710 --> 00:31:28.840
His name is Choice,
and he's at the farm.

00:31:28.840 --> 00:31:31.350
And when they used to
go there more often,

00:31:31.350 --> 00:31:33.960
a couple years ago, I
used to do hamburgers.

00:31:33.960 --> 00:31:36.720
And he was coming
next to me, because he

00:31:36.720 --> 00:31:37.910
was free on the farm.

00:31:37.910 --> 00:31:40.730
So he was helping
me with hamburgers.

00:31:40.730 --> 00:31:45.840
But no, these horses can live.

00:31:45.840 --> 00:31:48.845
When they leave the tour, it's
not because they are finished.

00:31:48.845 --> 00:31:51.150
It's just because it's
time for them to leave.

00:31:51.150 --> 00:31:56.350
After 16, 17 years old, we find
them either an adoption place,

00:31:56.350 --> 00:31:58.624
or we bring them to our farm.

00:31:58.624 --> 00:32:00.290
AUDIENCE: I think
over the past 30 years

00:32:00.290 --> 00:32:03.880
or so the Quebecois circus,
from Cirque du Soleil to Cavalia

00:32:03.880 --> 00:32:07.820
to Odysseo, has really
reshaped that whole genre.

00:32:07.820 --> 00:32:09.410
Why do you think that is?

00:32:09.410 --> 00:32:13.690
What have you seen change
from the early days to now?

00:32:13.690 --> 00:32:16.420
NORMAND LATOURELLE: Yeah, this
is a very difficult question

00:32:16.420 --> 00:32:17.330
to answer.

00:32:17.330 --> 00:32:20.760
How you define-- how
come-- and it's true.

00:32:20.760 --> 00:32:23.860
When you travel around the world
and you see the entertainment,

00:32:23.860 --> 00:32:26.090
live entertainment
world, you see

00:32:26.090 --> 00:32:28.750
a lot of people from
Quebec, like my province,

00:32:28.750 --> 00:32:30.370
like from Montreal and Quebec.

00:32:30.370 --> 00:32:31.030
Why is that?

00:32:31.030 --> 00:32:32.564
I cannot the answer.

00:32:32.564 --> 00:32:33.980
Maybe it's something
in the water.

00:32:37.040 --> 00:32:40.590
I don't know what it is,
to tell you the truth.

00:32:40.590 --> 00:32:44.980
That having been
said, we are a mix

00:32:44.980 --> 00:32:49.720
of-- I consider myself a mix
of American and European.

00:32:49.720 --> 00:32:52.950
And that's probably that we get
the influence of both worlds.

00:32:52.950 --> 00:32:57.300
And because we're a very
small, tiny French community--

00:32:57.300 --> 00:33:01.400
we're only three million
people over that ocean

00:33:01.400 --> 00:33:04.600
of English speakers--
we probably

00:33:04.600 --> 00:33:09.630
have developed some skills of
fighting and trying to express

00:33:09.630 --> 00:33:11.360
ourselves differently.

00:33:11.360 --> 00:33:15.560
That's maybe one of the reasons.

00:33:15.560 --> 00:33:19.410
And I was there for the
beginning of Cirque.

00:33:19.410 --> 00:33:23.890
And after Cirque, as you know
now, I've started Cavalia.

00:33:23.890 --> 00:33:28.590
And I think behind
me and other people

00:33:28.590 --> 00:33:31.970
is the idea of to trying to
do something new, different,

00:33:31.970 --> 00:33:34.020
and push the limits.

00:33:34.020 --> 00:33:36.140
That's probably what it is.

00:33:36.140 --> 00:33:38.260
That's what it is
for me, actually.

00:33:38.260 --> 00:33:40.310
AUDIENCE: When you're
doing live performances,

00:33:40.310 --> 00:33:43.310
is there a guideline
or rule of thumb,

00:33:43.310 --> 00:33:46.100
particularly during
the liberty portions,

00:33:46.100 --> 00:33:50.320
where if one of the
horses is not cooperating,

00:33:50.320 --> 00:33:52.560
someone will remove the
horse from the stage?

00:33:52.560 --> 00:33:55.200
Or will you always
just keep going

00:33:55.200 --> 00:33:57.909
and trying to bring the horse
back into the performance?

00:33:57.909 --> 00:33:59.450
NORMAND LATOURELLE:
Most of the time,

00:33:59.450 --> 00:34:02.300
we try to bring them
back to the performance.

00:34:02.300 --> 00:34:03.350
It did that happen.

00:34:03.350 --> 00:34:05.220
It did happen.

00:34:05.220 --> 00:34:09.550
It could happen that
if a horse really

00:34:09.550 --> 00:34:12.429
started to be-- because we
have a lot of stallions.

00:34:12.429 --> 00:34:15.409
We have only male horses, and
we have a lot of stallions.

00:34:15.409 --> 00:34:19.350
So if a stallion starts to
behave very badly, which

00:34:19.350 --> 00:34:24.150
could happen, at the
time, we will take a rope,

00:34:24.150 --> 00:34:26.860
bring him out.

00:34:26.860 --> 00:34:29.139
But that happens very rarely.

00:34:29.139 --> 00:34:32.179
Most of the time, we
let them, what I call,

00:34:32.179 --> 00:34:34.090
express themselves.

00:34:34.090 --> 00:34:38.670
And after a while,
because I've seen horses

00:34:38.670 --> 00:34:43.350
running for three minutes, and
running and kicking and having

00:34:43.350 --> 00:34:44.139
fun.

00:34:44.139 --> 00:34:46.679
So the rule is, let him.

00:34:46.679 --> 00:34:49.560
If he's not dangerous for
the horses, let him do it.

00:34:49.560 --> 00:34:51.639
And after two or three
minutes, he's just--

00:34:51.639 --> 00:34:53.070
[PANTING]

00:34:53.070 --> 00:34:54.340
OK, what do I do now?

00:34:54.340 --> 00:34:56.739
And then he's coming back.

00:34:56.739 --> 00:34:58.780
This is nature.

00:34:58.780 --> 00:35:00.260
This is so easy.

00:35:00.260 --> 00:35:01.630
You just have to read it.

00:35:01.630 --> 00:35:05.240
And it's also very interesting,
because I repeat that

00:35:05.240 --> 00:35:09.390
to whoever is next to horses,
probably because I'm not

00:35:09.390 --> 00:35:10.860
next to horses I can say it.

00:35:10.860 --> 00:35:13.770
I say to the people, the
horses never makes mistakes.

00:35:13.770 --> 00:35:15.620
It's the human who
makes mistakes.

00:35:15.620 --> 00:35:18.320
It's just changing
the perspective.

00:35:18.320 --> 00:35:20.030
You ask something to the horse.

00:35:20.030 --> 00:35:23.170
If he doesn't do it, it's
because you didn't ask right,

00:35:23.170 --> 00:35:28.600
or you didn't take the time
to let him answer right.

00:35:28.600 --> 00:35:32.490
And that's the
philosophy behind it.

00:35:32.490 --> 00:35:34.350
But it's easy to say for me.

00:35:34.350 --> 00:35:38.300
But for the trainers,
some of the girls

00:35:38.300 --> 00:35:41.880
are five feet four
inches next to a horse

00:35:41.880 --> 00:35:44.420
that is twice her size.

00:35:44.420 --> 00:35:48.950
I can see sometimes, OK,
that's a nice philosophy

00:35:48.950 --> 00:35:50.670
but it's a big animal.

00:35:50.670 --> 00:35:52.420
It's a question of balance.

00:35:52.420 --> 00:35:55.050
I think it's always--
that's in life.

00:35:55.050 --> 00:35:57.450
Everything in life for me,
it's a question of balance.

00:35:57.450 --> 00:35:58.300
It's the same thing.

00:35:58.300 --> 00:36:01.410
Next to an animal, even
more, next to any animal,

00:36:01.410 --> 00:36:02.670
it's a question of balance.

00:36:02.670 --> 00:36:06.290
If you want to dominate too
much, he won't like you.

00:36:06.290 --> 00:36:08.780
If you want to be his
friend, he will like you.

00:36:08.780 --> 00:36:11.470
FEMALE SPEAKER: What
was your childhood like?

00:36:11.470 --> 00:36:13.820
How did your parents
influence you?

00:36:13.820 --> 00:36:16.160
And if your mother
was here, what would

00:36:16.160 --> 00:36:20.379
she say was the first sign that
you would be who you are today?

00:36:20.379 --> 00:36:22.420
NORMAND LATOURELLE: Oh,
that's a moving question,

00:36:22.420 --> 00:36:26.970
because my mother just passed
away about eight months ago.

00:36:26.970 --> 00:36:30.630
And my mother, even if I was
doing very stupid and crazy

00:36:30.630 --> 00:36:34.970
things when I was young,
which my father didn't like,

00:36:34.970 --> 00:36:37.670
but my mother
always supported me.

00:36:37.670 --> 00:36:44.430
And probably my mother
gave me the courage,

00:36:44.430 --> 00:36:48.800
as far as my idea,
of bringing me to.

00:36:48.800 --> 00:36:53.680
Because I'm one of the rare
guys who has the two votes.

00:36:53.680 --> 00:36:55.820
I'm producing the show.

00:36:55.820 --> 00:36:58.680
So financially, I'm
involved, and I'm creating

00:36:58.680 --> 00:37:00.840
the show, which is very rare.

00:37:00.840 --> 00:37:03.450
Usually, you see
someone who'll create

00:37:03.450 --> 00:37:07.075
and you find someone who brings
the money in and produces.

00:37:07.075 --> 00:37:07.700
I have the two.

00:37:10.410 --> 00:37:13.080
The reason why I'm
like that, probably

00:37:13.080 --> 00:37:16.780
is because nobody at first when
I started to talk about, I'm

00:37:16.780 --> 00:37:19.910
going to do a great show with
horses, they were looking at me

00:37:19.910 --> 00:37:21.860
like-- and if you
go to a producer

00:37:21.860 --> 00:37:24.800
or whoever has
money to tell him,

00:37:24.800 --> 00:37:27.010
I'm going to do a
great show with horses,

00:37:27.010 --> 00:37:30.160
it's going to be very modern.

00:37:30.160 --> 00:37:34.810
And 10 years ago,
people just don't come.

00:37:34.810 --> 00:37:39.260
So I said, OK, I'm going
to support my idea.

00:37:39.260 --> 00:37:42.980
The reality is the producer
suffers more than the creator

00:37:42.980 --> 00:37:47.060
because I'm spending
so much money.

00:37:47.060 --> 00:37:50.140
But I am just pushing my
idea as far as I could.

00:37:50.140 --> 00:37:52.850
And that's probably
from my mother.

00:37:52.850 --> 00:37:59.760
And because it's become very
personal, also in my family,

00:37:59.760 --> 00:38:02.180
my oldest brother is disabled.

00:38:02.180 --> 00:38:07.740
And I've been very
supportive of him.

00:38:07.740 --> 00:38:14.500
Even today, he's
66 67 right now.

00:38:14.500 --> 00:38:17.410
Very supportive of
him, but I always

00:38:17.410 --> 00:38:20.130
felt I was very blessed
compared to him.

00:38:20.130 --> 00:38:22.610
And I always felt,
even when I was young,

00:38:22.610 --> 00:38:24.340
I had to do twice
more because he

00:38:24.340 --> 00:38:27.710
couldn't do what he deserved.

00:38:27.710 --> 00:38:30.640
And I just always
pushed the limit.

00:38:30.640 --> 00:38:33.020
It's probably the
combination of two.

00:38:36.151 --> 00:38:40.390
I like to say I was
born on a sidewalk.

00:38:40.390 --> 00:38:44.380
I passed my young
age in an alley.

00:38:44.380 --> 00:38:48.920
And I became a
teenager in the street.

00:38:48.920 --> 00:38:51.370
That's probably how
to resume my life.

00:38:51.370 --> 00:38:55.240
And then when I grew up, I
just traveled around the world.

00:38:55.240 --> 00:38:57.038
That's who I am.

00:38:57.038 --> 00:38:58.490
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:38:58.490 --> 00:39:00.860
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I noticed
in the teaser clip,

00:39:00.860 --> 00:39:02.436
there was a pool of water.

00:39:02.436 --> 00:39:04.560
And some of the horses were
going through the water

00:39:04.560 --> 00:39:06.850
and the acrobats were
jumping through the water.

00:39:06.850 --> 00:39:08.700
Do you actually have
a pool on stage?

00:39:08.700 --> 00:39:10.380
And does that
introduce other kinds

00:39:10.380 --> 00:39:13.422
of difficulties or challenges?

00:39:13.422 --> 00:39:15.800
NORMAND LATOURELLE: Definitely,
a lot of challenges.

00:39:15.800 --> 00:39:18.390
We fill the stage.

00:39:18.390 --> 00:39:20.980
Again, the stage is about
the size of a hockey rink.

00:39:20.980 --> 00:39:24.640
We filled it in about
one minute, 30 seconds

00:39:24.640 --> 00:39:26.960
with 40,000 gallons of water.

00:39:26.960 --> 00:39:30.030
Again, this is a touring show.

00:39:30.030 --> 00:39:37.140
It's very complicated, because
we change location everywhere

00:39:37.140 --> 00:39:37.850
we go.

00:39:37.850 --> 00:39:39.402
So it has to be totally level.

00:39:39.402 --> 00:39:40.860
Because if it's
not level, you know

00:39:40.860 --> 00:39:42.720
what happens with the water.

00:39:42.720 --> 00:39:44.200
So it's very challenging.

00:39:44.200 --> 00:39:47.990
And it's one of the most
technically challenging parts

00:39:47.990 --> 00:39:49.020
of the show.

00:39:49.020 --> 00:39:56.500
But I thought I wanted--
Odysseo is-- let's say the word.

00:39:56.500 --> 00:39:59.470
It's an odyssey,
where men and horses

00:39:59.470 --> 00:40:01.850
go to discover the most
beautiful landscape

00:40:01.850 --> 00:40:02.660
in the world.

00:40:02.660 --> 00:40:05.540
So they're just
traveling together.

00:40:05.540 --> 00:40:07.200
That's why I call it odyssey.

00:40:07.200 --> 00:40:11.662
And in the end, "eau" is
because of the water coming.

00:40:11.662 --> 00:40:16.820
And I think you cannot-- and
the stage reveals a lot about

00:40:16.820 --> 00:40:17.630
nature.

00:40:17.630 --> 00:40:20.260
So you cannot reveal about
nature without talking about

00:40:20.260 --> 00:40:22.810
the water, which is
the source of life,

00:40:22.810 --> 00:40:27.280
which is also
where animals meet.

00:40:27.280 --> 00:40:31.380
If you go to anywhere, the
animals, every kind of animal,

00:40:31.380 --> 00:40:35.420
meet, including humans,
around a source of water.

00:40:35.420 --> 00:40:37.710
And I could not
do a show talking

00:40:37.710 --> 00:40:40.320
about the relationship
of men and horses

00:40:40.320 --> 00:40:44.020
and traveling throughout the
world without having water,

00:40:44.020 --> 00:40:45.690
even if it's very challenging.

00:40:45.690 --> 00:40:48.780
Because this show, again,
you have to see it,

00:40:48.780 --> 00:40:52.420
but it's the biggest
touring show in the world.

00:40:52.420 --> 00:40:56.040
We have about 120 semi
trailers when we move.

00:40:56.040 --> 00:41:00.220
If you compare to the biggest
rock 'n' roll tour, the Rolling

00:41:00.220 --> 00:41:02.713
Stones or U2, they have only 65.

00:41:05.310 --> 00:41:08.640
I mean, it's a big tour.

00:41:08.640 --> 00:41:11.340
And the big tent
is one of a kind,

00:41:11.340 --> 00:41:17.140
because I didn't want to
have the feeling of a circus.

00:41:17.140 --> 00:41:21.690
I'm not a circus guy,
where you see the ring

00:41:21.690 --> 00:41:23.430
and everything goes around.

00:41:23.430 --> 00:41:24.510
I didn't want that.

00:41:24.510 --> 00:41:29.910
So we really created a space
that is like a real auditorium.

00:41:29.910 --> 00:41:33.310
And people are sitting in the
auditorium, like here, facing

00:41:33.310 --> 00:41:36.740
the stage, but the
stage is very, very big.

00:41:36.740 --> 00:41:38.520
And there's no obstruction.

00:41:38.520 --> 00:41:41.382
Most of the tents you see in
the world, even the Cirque du

00:41:41.382 --> 00:41:46.170
Soleil tents, the big one, you
see a mast next to the stage.

00:41:46.170 --> 00:41:50.770
When you get to see Odysseo,
you see no obstruction.

00:41:50.770 --> 00:41:51.740
There's no mast.

00:41:51.740 --> 00:41:53.520
Everything is
supported by-- if you

00:41:53.520 --> 00:41:57.850
pass nearby the tent over
there, you see three arches.

00:41:57.850 --> 00:42:03.340
We support 80 tons of equipment
there but with these arches.

00:42:03.340 --> 00:42:08.750
So if you're into engineering,
just go and watch carefully.

00:42:08.750 --> 00:42:10.560
It's a marvel of engineering.

00:42:10.560 --> 00:42:13.500
This is just an amazing
engineering piece.

00:42:13.500 --> 00:42:18.140
Because when you tour, rock
'n' roll tour in an arena,

00:42:18.140 --> 00:42:23.970
usually the maximum weight they
put to the ceiling is 50 tons.

00:42:23.970 --> 00:42:25.520
And we have 80.

00:42:25.520 --> 00:42:28.570
One of the most important
elements of the show

00:42:28.570 --> 00:42:31.490
is a merry-go-round that
appears from the ceiling.

00:42:31.490 --> 00:42:33.050
Again, you're under a tent.

00:42:33.050 --> 00:42:36.070
You're not in a
permanent theater.

00:42:36.070 --> 00:42:41.430
And the merry-go-round is
very big, weighs 18 tons.

00:42:41.430 --> 00:42:44.887
And we do an
acrobatic act on it.

00:42:44.887 --> 00:42:46.470
And this part, I
mean, you've seen it.

00:42:46.470 --> 00:42:51.630
It's just magical and
brings you to a dream world.

00:42:51.630 --> 00:42:57.530
Again, this is because I pushed
the idea and made it happen.

00:42:57.530 --> 00:43:00.280
That's the thing-- you just have
an idea and you make it happen.

00:43:00.280 --> 00:43:04.210
So whatever it costs, is it
possible or not, let's do it.

00:43:04.210 --> 00:43:09.251
And that's what is defining,
pretty much, Odysseo.

00:43:09.251 --> 00:43:10.750
AUDIENCE: You have
dozens of horses.

00:43:10.750 --> 00:43:14.115
Do you ever acquire horses
as your show is traveling?

00:43:14.115 --> 00:43:15.740
Because, I mean,
you're in places where

00:43:15.740 --> 00:43:18.439
there's horse communities or?

00:43:18.439 --> 00:43:19.480
NORMAND LATOURELLE: Yeah.

00:43:19.480 --> 00:43:21.190
Yeah, we do, actually.

00:43:21.190 --> 00:43:21.960
Yeah, we do.

00:43:21.960 --> 00:43:25.470
We have horses--
yesterday, I was

00:43:25.470 --> 00:43:27.000
talking to one of
the grooms, and we

00:43:27.000 --> 00:43:30.130
have one horse from
Australia, because Cavalia

00:43:30.130 --> 00:43:31.340
went to Australia.

00:43:31.340 --> 00:43:33.330
And after a while, we
brought the horse back

00:43:33.330 --> 00:43:34.210
to North America.

00:43:34.210 --> 00:43:37.190
And he's now touring
with Odysseo.

00:43:37.190 --> 00:43:41.010
And we have horses from Arizona,
because we were in Arizona.

00:43:41.010 --> 00:43:43.800
We have horses from California.

00:43:43.800 --> 00:43:47.970
And we always look
for good horses.

00:43:47.970 --> 00:43:49.820
And they are everywhere.

00:43:49.820 --> 00:43:53.860
There's no specific place
where we buy horses.

00:43:53.860 --> 00:43:56.020
But of course we have
a lot of-- again,

00:43:56.020 --> 00:43:59.590
I just might repeat here, but
we have a lot of Spanish horses.

00:43:59.590 --> 00:44:03.180
So these ones, of course,
we go to buy them in Spain.

00:44:03.180 --> 00:44:05.994
But other than that, we buy
through the course of the tour.

00:44:05.994 --> 00:44:07.910
AUDIENCE: All right, two
more quick questions.

00:44:07.910 --> 00:44:10.963
Which market have you
made the most money in

00:44:10.963 --> 00:44:14.310
or is most popular, where
you have the most response?

00:44:14.310 --> 00:44:16.740
And have you ever thought
of having a permanent show,

00:44:16.740 --> 00:44:18.390
like a permanent building?

00:44:18.390 --> 00:44:20.960
NORMAND LATOURELLE: Yeah.

00:44:20.960 --> 00:44:26.940
Well, there's a big difference
between Cavalia and Odysseo.

00:44:26.940 --> 00:44:29.030
Cavalia made money.

00:44:29.030 --> 00:44:32.927
Odysseo is spending money.

00:44:32.927 --> 00:44:34.510
That's why it's worth
it for you to go

00:44:34.510 --> 00:44:39.240
see how do you spend money.

00:44:39.240 --> 00:44:44.070
With no joking, California is
a very good, very good market.

00:44:44.070 --> 00:44:46.230
We were in San
Francisco not long ago.

00:44:46.230 --> 00:44:47.820
We did fantastic.

00:44:47.820 --> 00:44:51.160
We just arrived a couple
months ago from Irvine.

00:44:51.160 --> 00:44:52.490
We're returning to Irvine.

00:44:52.490 --> 00:44:54.790
So California is a great market.

00:44:54.790 --> 00:45:00.880
Also, in terms of economies,
which is very important, when

00:45:00.880 --> 00:45:03.950
you are into entertainment, live
entertainment in California,

00:45:03.950 --> 00:45:08.250
you don't pay tax, which
I mean, on the ticket.

00:45:08.250 --> 00:45:13.080
If you go back where I
live, you pay 15% of tax.

00:45:13.080 --> 00:45:14.869
So it does make
a big difference.

00:45:14.869 --> 00:45:16.910
AUDIENCE: It's the only
thing we're not taxed on.

00:45:16.910 --> 00:45:17.680
NORMAND LATOURELLE: I'm sorry?

00:45:17.680 --> 00:45:20.304
AUDIENCE: It's the one thing in
California you're not taxed on!

00:45:20.304 --> 00:45:21.972
NORMAND LATOURELLE:
Well, yeah, exactly.

00:45:21.972 --> 00:45:23.180
I mean, you have other taxes.

00:45:23.180 --> 00:45:24.555
I don't say you
don't have taxes.

00:45:24.555 --> 00:45:26.560
I just say, we're not
taxed, because we're

00:45:26.560 --> 00:45:30.260
live entertainment, which is
fantastic, which is fantastic.

00:45:30.260 --> 00:45:32.900
So in terms of business,
doing business in California

00:45:32.900 --> 00:45:35.820
is very good for us.

00:45:35.820 --> 00:45:39.240
Where we stayed the longest?

00:45:39.240 --> 00:45:42.000
Actually, we return many
times so it's hard to say.

00:45:42.000 --> 00:45:44.670
But Cavalia, the first
show is now in China.

00:45:44.670 --> 00:45:48.630
It has been performing in
Beijing for six months,

00:45:48.630 --> 00:45:50.960
and we are still extending.

00:45:50.960 --> 00:45:56.750
So this is a revelation, because
we don't know-- we didn't know.

00:45:56.750 --> 00:45:58.430
And there's no horses in China.

00:45:58.430 --> 00:45:59.650
There's very, very little.

00:45:59.650 --> 00:46:03.670
There's a lot of horses in
their culture, a lot of horses

00:46:03.670 --> 00:46:05.590
in their mythology.

00:46:05.590 --> 00:46:09.220
But the reality is there's
not that many horses in China.

00:46:09.220 --> 00:46:13.230
Very little unless
you go far north.

00:46:13.230 --> 00:46:16.710
So that having been said,
the first show for whoever

00:46:16.710 --> 00:46:18.590
has seen it, the
first show there's

00:46:18.590 --> 00:46:23.600
two small horses that
open the first act.

00:46:23.600 --> 00:46:27.190
And here we see horses.

00:46:27.190 --> 00:46:29.190
We applaud, and it's the
beginning of the show.

00:46:29.190 --> 00:46:31.350
Over there, they're like kids.

00:46:31.350 --> 00:46:32.910
I'm talking about the audience.

00:46:32.910 --> 00:46:36.960
You hear "woooo!" every show.

00:46:36.960 --> 00:46:41.877
It's surprising, because
they don't see live horses.

00:46:41.877 --> 00:46:43.210
You're in the middle of Beijing.

00:46:43.210 --> 00:46:46.370
I don't know if any of
you have been to Beijing,

00:46:46.370 --> 00:46:49.050
but it's a monstrous city.

00:46:49.050 --> 00:46:52.030
I mean, San Francisco
and Los Angeles

00:46:52.030 --> 00:46:56.436
are very small
compared to Beijing.

00:46:56.436 --> 00:46:59.190
So that's where we
spend a lot of time.

00:46:59.190 --> 00:47:03.210
And of course,
Montreal, my hometown,

00:47:03.210 --> 00:47:07.140
I mean, when we go
there, we're big stars.

00:47:07.140 --> 00:47:12.740
At least one city we're a big
star in the world, my own city!

00:47:12.740 --> 00:47:14.920
We do very good
business in Canada too.

00:47:14.920 --> 00:47:15.860
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:47:15.860 --> 00:47:17.680
AUDIENCE: My question is,
can you comment a little bit

00:47:17.680 --> 00:47:18.540
on the logistics?

00:47:18.540 --> 00:47:21.130
You have 120 trailers
that are going around?

00:47:21.130 --> 00:47:22.230
NORMAND LATOURELLE: Yeah,
semi-trailers for Odysseo.

00:47:22.230 --> 00:47:22.900
AUDIENCE: I'm just
trying to imagine

00:47:22.900 --> 00:47:24.780
all the people that you need.

00:47:24.780 --> 00:47:27.459
You have 45 performers,
I think you mentioned.

00:47:27.459 --> 00:47:29.750
You've got people that have
to take care of the horses.

00:47:29.750 --> 00:47:32.370
You need people to set up
the tents, the lighting,

00:47:32.370 --> 00:47:34.139
the orchestra, the
musicians, all that.

00:47:34.139 --> 00:47:35.680
How many people are
touring with you?

00:47:35.680 --> 00:47:37.410
And how do you handle
all these logistics?

00:47:37.410 --> 00:47:38.451
NORMAND LATOURELLE: Yeah.

00:47:38.451 --> 00:47:43.630
We have 120-- I was going
to say 120 semi-trailers.

00:47:43.630 --> 00:47:44.350
That's true.

00:47:44.350 --> 00:47:49.690
But 120 permanent staff
touring with us full time.

00:47:49.690 --> 00:47:52.140
We run the show at
about 200 people.

00:47:52.140 --> 00:47:55.520
So the 80 people every
day are local people.

00:47:55.520 --> 00:47:59.140
When we set up, when we
move, because we move

00:47:59.140 --> 00:48:03.940
this big tour in about 17 days,
from the last show in a city

00:48:03.940 --> 00:48:08.710
to the first show in the next
city, and then we are about 200

00:48:08.710 --> 00:48:12.780
per day, about 200 to 250
people per day to help

00:48:12.780 --> 00:48:16.150
to set up and dismantle.

00:48:16.150 --> 00:48:20.080
The logistics, I guess
we get used to it.

00:48:20.080 --> 00:48:23.300
We have fantastic people
taking care of all the details.

00:48:23.300 --> 00:48:25.940
There's a lot to be done.

00:48:25.940 --> 00:48:27.560
There's a lot to achieve.

00:48:27.560 --> 00:48:29.720
I guess it's a little
bit like the army.

00:48:29.720 --> 00:48:31.840
When it's time to move,
you just back your truck

00:48:31.840 --> 00:48:35.130
and you just move and
set up in the next city.

00:48:35.130 --> 00:48:38.240
And it's also
personal logistics.

00:48:38.240 --> 00:48:42.080
Because everyone
lives in an apartment.

00:48:42.080 --> 00:48:43.080
But you know what it is.

00:48:43.080 --> 00:48:47.300
When you tour, you
start with one luggage,

00:48:47.300 --> 00:48:49.620
and then you have two,
three, four, five.

00:48:49.620 --> 00:48:52.010
There's a rider who
left us yesterday

00:48:52.010 --> 00:48:53.410
after five years of touring.

00:48:53.410 --> 00:48:54.717
She went back home.

00:48:54.717 --> 00:48:56.800
And she said, I don't know
how I'm going to do it.

00:48:56.800 --> 00:48:58.370
I have seven luggage.

00:48:58.370 --> 00:49:00.560
And I said, oh, I don't
think Air Canada will

00:49:00.560 --> 00:49:02.680
accept seven luggage from you.

00:49:02.680 --> 00:49:08.790
But the reality is, we
have to have a container,

00:49:08.790 --> 00:49:11.150
and we call it an extra
luggage container.

00:49:11.150 --> 00:49:15.400
And it's all part of what we do.

00:49:15.400 --> 00:49:19.710
And it's mainly because we have
very good people who do it.

00:49:19.710 --> 00:49:23.090
AUDIENCE: There are many really
magical parts of your show.

00:49:23.090 --> 00:49:27.370
One of the parts that was most
astounding, as someone who's

00:49:27.370 --> 00:49:30.720
ridden horses, was
there's a trick rider who

00:49:30.720 --> 00:49:33.530
goes under the belly of the
horse and back up to the top

00:49:33.530 --> 00:49:36.170
while the horse is galloping.

00:49:36.170 --> 00:49:37.730
Can you tell me
a little bit more

00:49:37.730 --> 00:49:40.990
about how long they've
trained for that?

00:49:40.990 --> 00:49:42.740
I've never seen anything
like that before.

00:49:42.740 --> 00:49:44.560
That was just amazing.

00:49:44.560 --> 00:49:46.950
Or where that trick came from?

00:49:46.950 --> 00:49:48.900
NORMAND LATOURELLE:
Well, this number,

00:49:48.900 --> 00:49:50.420
we call it Cossack riding.

00:49:50.420 --> 00:49:55.710
And it's from the
far part of Russia.

00:49:55.710 --> 00:49:59.610
They've started this type
of riding over there.

00:49:59.610 --> 00:50:04.630
And there are very few
guys who are doing it,

00:50:04.630 --> 00:50:06.520
but the reality, if
you look carefully,

00:50:06.520 --> 00:50:10.940
the horse that does it is
very tall, and this guy

00:50:10.940 --> 00:50:13.600
has enough space to move.

00:50:13.600 --> 00:50:15.960
But you have to
establish a real trust,

00:50:15.960 --> 00:50:18.590
because nobody is
riding the horse.

00:50:18.590 --> 00:50:21.400
He's just going full
speed and around.

00:50:21.400 --> 00:50:23.840
You don't want to
stop, or him to stop.

00:50:23.840 --> 00:50:26.050
You don't want him to slow down.

00:50:26.050 --> 00:50:30.730
So they get to train him, and
finally he goes under the belly

00:50:30.730 --> 00:50:34.180
and comes back after every show.

00:50:34.180 --> 00:50:36.235
And it's very
spectacular, very scary.

00:50:40.440 --> 00:50:43.600
My hands get wet every
time I see him doing it.

00:50:43.600 --> 00:50:44.480
Will I do it?

00:50:44.480 --> 00:50:46.680
No.

00:50:46.680 --> 00:50:49.790
But he's an athlete and that's
what he does for a living,

00:50:49.790 --> 00:50:52.380
believe it or not.

00:50:52.380 --> 00:50:54.310
But it's very impressive.

00:50:54.310 --> 00:50:58.850
And the show brings you to
a lot of action sometimes.

00:50:58.850 --> 00:51:02.030
And sometimes, it's
very smooth, beautiful.

00:51:02.030 --> 00:51:08.850
And this show brings
you to a lot of-- it's

00:51:08.850 --> 00:51:10.090
just a feel-good show.

00:51:10.090 --> 00:51:11.660
After the show, I say, wow.

00:51:11.660 --> 00:51:13.620
I've seen something different.

00:51:13.620 --> 00:51:17.410
I've seen something that
animals [? live ?] well.

00:51:17.410 --> 00:51:19.370
They seem happy.

00:51:19.370 --> 00:51:23.490
And it's just a
beautiful show, I think.

00:51:23.490 --> 00:51:26.420
And you just said it,
but I like to repeat it.

00:51:26.420 --> 00:51:30.090
Because there's nothing
harsh in this show.

00:51:30.090 --> 00:51:32.780
There's nothing that
you can say, "ohhh."

00:51:32.780 --> 00:51:34.260
It's just beautiful.

00:51:34.260 --> 00:51:36.730
That's the idea behind it.

00:51:36.730 --> 00:51:39.370
FEMALE SPEAKER: Thank you so
much for being here today.

00:51:39.370 --> 00:51:39.870
NORMAND LATOURELLE: Thank you.

00:51:39.870 --> 00:51:40.810
Thank you very much.

00:51:40.810 --> 00:51:44.358
[APPLAUSE]

